How does tracking and adding changes make developers' lives easier?
-It's much safer to experiment with new ideas for your product.
-Identifying where/when bugs occured and reverting back to code without bugs is very easy with version control.

What is a commit?
-A commit is a forever saved and time stamped version of your code.
What are the best practices for commit messages?
-They should summarize concisely the changes that were made in this version or anything unique to this version as opposed to others.

What does the HEAD^ argument mean?
-HEAD^ is the most recent commit prior to the one you are currently working on.

What are the 3 stages of a git change and how do you move a file from one stage to the other?
-pull up to date master
-commit changes
-push changes and merge your changes branch back to master

Write a handy cheatsheet of the commands you need to commit your changes.
-git status
-git add . or git add <filename>
-git commit -m "comments go here"

What is a pull request and how do you create and merge one?
-git pull
-ensures that any changes made on the GitHub repo will be pulled to your local machine so that you don't have problems pushing your changes back to GitHub

Why are pull requests preferred when working with teams?
-ensures that each team member is always working on the most up to date version of the collaboration